name: Containerboard, 100% recycled, average production, at mill
description:
Containerboard, 100% recycled (recycled linerboard and recycled corrugating medium), average U.S. production, at mill. By-products were allocated 0% of the impacts to enable the user to choose and apply their own allocation method more easily.  All flows are production-weighted means. Data were developed for a full LCA that was critically reviewed. Reviewers were: Mr. Jamie Meil, Athena Institute - review panel Chairman; Ms. Lindita Bushi, Athena Institute; Ms Melissa Hamilton, Earthshift. 

The unit process includes pulp production from recovered paper, papermaking, and preparation for shipping to customers. Net purchased energy is included, but upstream flows associated with its generation are excluded. Flows associated with transportation of inputs from the technosphere are included.  Product transportation is excluded.

processDocumentation.timeDescription: Primary data collected from participating companies and associations for their operational activities are representative for 2010.
processDocumentation.samplingDescription: The survey included results from 24 containerboard mills representing 4.2 million short tons per year (TPY) of 100% recycled containerboard, nearly 56% of 2010 production volume.
processDocumentation.restrictionsDescription: All information can be accessed by everybody.

exchanges.description: 7.06E-04 dry kg, 648 dry kg/m3 (http://www.corrim.org/pubs/reports/2010/phase2/Module_L.pdf)Includes bar. Containerboard made form 100%-recylced fiber does not use logs and chips for pulp production. Howerver, some of the containerboard form 100%-recycled fiber is produced at mills that also produce containerboard from virgin fiber. Some of these mills produce more energy using spent liquor and self-generated hogged fuel thant they need in their virgin operations. In theses cases, it was assumed that extra energy form these fuels was "sold" to the recyled product and hence, the quantity of chips and logs required to produce that sold energy was allocated to the recycled product. Wood (logs and chips) usage in the process is distrubuted as follows: 9.5% in self-generated hogged fuel, and 90.5% in black liquor.
